reason: The newton (N) is the SI unit of force, defined as the force required to accelerate a mass of one kilogram at one meter per second squared.
The newton meter (N·m) is a derived unit representing torque or moment of force in the SI system.

The coulomb per square meter (C/m²) is a unit representing electric charge per unit area, commonly used in surface charge density.

The term 'per ampere' (A⁻¹) represents a derived unit inverse to electric current, used in quantities like magnetic reluctance or inverse current sensitivity.
The farad (F) is the SI unit of capacitance, defined as the ability to store one coulomb of charge per volt of potential difference.
The dalton (Da), also called the unified atomic mass unit, is a unit of mass used to express atomic and molecular weights.
The term 'second power 4' (s⁴) represents a derived unit of time to the fourth power, used in some specialized physical calculations.
The term 'per kilogram' (kg⁻¹) represents a derived unit inverse to mass, used in quantities like specific activity or mass-specific properties.

The joule per mole (J/mol) is a unit of molar energy, representing energy per amount of substance in thermodynamic and chemical systems.
The becquerel (Bq) is the SI unit of radioactivity, defined as one nuclear decay per second.
The byte (B) is a fundamental unit of digital information storage, typically representing 8 bits of data.
The coulomb per kilogram (C/kg) is a unit of exposure to ionizing radiation, representing charge per unit mass of air.
The ampere per square meter (A/m²) is a unit of current density, representing electric current flow per unit cross-sectional area.

The joule (J) is the SI unit of energy, defined as the work done when a force of one newton displaces an object by one meter.

The electron volt (eV) is a unit of energy equal to the work done on an electron moving through an electric potential difference of one volt.
The joule per kilogram per kelvin (J/(kg·K)) is the SI unit of specific entropy or specific heat capacity.

The hertz (Hz) is the SI unit of frequency, defined as one cycle per second.

The reciprocal second (s⁻¹) is a derived unit representing frequency or rate, equivalent to hertz in some contexts.

The tesla (T) is the SI unit of magnetic flux density, representing one weber per square meter of magnetic field strength.
The watt (W) is the SI unit of power, defined as one joule of energy transferred per second.
The gray per second (Gy/s) is a unit representing the rate of absorbed radiation dose, where one gray equals one joule per kilogram.
